			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				My name is Manda, and I am the woman in this article. Firstly, I want to say that I do not blame EQ for our problems, that is just the source of his addiction. Secondly, I want to add to the very rude person who started to down grade my character because I am unmarried with a daughter, that you do not know me, you do not know my situations, my circumstances, or anything about me. Until you do, you have no right to pass any judgments on me.<BR>
<BR>
I know that my fiance is an adult and is capable of making his own decisions. But, that is the tricky thing with decisions, you judgment becomes clouded by the source of your addiction.<BR>
<BR>
I find it funny how someone could say the slightest negative thing about EverQuest, and insults are thrown. I find that very cult like. And I am sure I will get slammed for this too.<BR>
<BR>
Since this article has appeared, I have started to get some no so nice e mail. I guess I should be happy that they took the time to look my information up to get an e mail address. You know, time away from the game and all. But, at the same time, that is very scary for me, and very UNCALLED for. And I am sure I will receive a fair amount of criticism from this post as well.<BR>
<BR>
Everyone does not have the same playing habits or responsibliites. Some play 15 hours a week total, some play 80. If you have no responsiblities, that is fine, so be it. But if you do and you are playing 80 hours a week, where do you responsiblities lie?<BR>
<BR>
I never expected or demanded my fiance give up EQ&gt; Just moderate how much time he spends on it, in order to  have a family. His daughter is experiencing a lot of first in life, milestones he will never be able to have because his addiction has led him astray from that. <BR>
<BR>
I never blamed EQ for my problems, I simply think it should be labeled for it's addictive nature.<BR>
<BR>
I do play EQ. I play about three hours a week. Now, I do not expect my fiance to play as little as I do. I was once addicted to the game, so I completely understand. But, I do not think having a family that plays EQ is the solution for us. I would rather my children have real life memories to hold onto, instead of those in a digital fantasy land.
				</font>
			</td>

