			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				This is really kind of absurd.  Sure, there are EQ addicts.  I'll bet a lot of money that it hasn't ruined nearly as many relationships as plain ol' chat rooms, though.  I got evercrack about a year ago, right after a pretty nasty breakup, and simply by distracting me from reality, it helped a lot.  I've got depressive disorder, and believe me it sucks.  When I really get down, I sometimes need something to distract me.  My girlfriend of the past three months (four on the 14h - v-day!) is about as active as it gets in her church, music stuff, community service, etc., so when she's not around to talk to or hang out with, I sign on for a little mindless gaming.<BR>
  My grades dropped a bit last year, and are still down.  But that's not because of Everquest.  It's simply because when I get down I don't give a damn about school, or anything else for that matter.  If I can stir my stump, I call up my girlfriend or play some EQ.  If not I sit in my room and contemplate how useless life is (and it's very useless indeed, as far as I can tell).  EQ has only been a benefit in my life, or so I believe.<BR>
  My girlfriend doesn't object to me playing EQ because it keeps me out of trouble while she's too busy to do the job.  I also only play 15 hours aa week on average.  What?  Moderation?  What a novel idea... those of you who get to level 30 in a month or so without powerleveling should give it a try sometime.<BR>
  Give EQ a break.  EQ doesn't *censored* people up, people *censored* people up.  Props to Verant, they may well have saved my life by making this game.  Also, thanks to all the people who have made it an enjoyable experience to play.  EQ is only a problem for people who let it become a problem.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
